Simplify your `${jetty.base}/webapps/app-404.xml` to just ...

``` xml
&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot;?&gt;
&lt;!DOCTYPE Configure PUBLIC &quot;-//Jetty//Configure//EN&quot;
   &quot;http://www.eclipse.org/jetty/configure_9_3.dtd&quot;&gt;
&lt;Configure class=&quot;org.eclipse.jetty.webapp.WebAppContext&quot;&gt;
  &lt;Set name=&quot;contextPath&quot;&gt;/&lt;/Set&gt;
  &lt;Set name=&quot;war&quot;&gt;&lt;Env name=&quot;JETTY_APPS&quot; /&gt;/404.war&lt;/Set&gt;
&lt;/Configure&gt;
```

The `Configuration` classes are not meant to be setup on an individual webapp basis like you are attempting.

If you need annotations support, or plus support, then enable one (or both) of those modules on your `${jetty.base}` using the normal (and recommended) `${jetty.base}` and `${jetty.home}` split configuration (there are `annotations` and `plus` named modules available, use them)

One other note, if you are using &quot;stock Jetty and there&#39;s no customization&quot;, then don&#39;t use the `&lt;Env&gt;` xml element, as its got side effects that don&#39;t play nice with the various modules that require a forked JVM (such as most logging modules), use the pre-existing `&lt;Property name=&quot;jetty.webapps&quot;&gt;`, it will work in all `${jetty.base}` setups.

``` xml
 &lt;Set name=&quot;war&quot;&gt;&lt;Property name=&quot;jetty.webapps&quot;/&gt;/404.war&lt;/Set&gt;
