Is a Java [switch expression](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/13/language/switch-expressions.html) introduced in Java 12. Pre-Java-12 it would have been written is a switch statement:

          switch (  duck[r][c] ) {
            case EYE: window.setColor(0,0,0); break;
            case BILL: window.setColor(255,0,0); break;
            case LEGS: window.setColor(100,100,0); break;
            case BODY: window.setColor(200,200,0); break;
          }

Switch statements require their case labels to be followed by _a colon_.

Note that a switch expression _returns a value_, whereas a switch statement does not. Consider the following:

```java
String s = switch(i) {
  case 1 -&gt; &quot;one&quot;;
  case 2 -&gt; &quot;two&quot;;
  default -&gt; &quot;more&quot;;
}
```

To achieve equivalent behavior, you&#39;d have to rewrite:

```java
String convert(int i) {
  switch(i) {
    case 1: return &quot;one&quot;;
    case 2: return &quot;two&quot;;
    default: return &quot;more&quot;;
  }
}

String s = convert(i);
```

